{\pard \s1 \f1\fs32\ql\sb240\sa180\b {\*\bkmkstart whatismultimarkdowntolyx}{\*\bkmkend whatismultimarkdowntolyx}What is MultiMarkdown to LyX?\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 MultiMarkdown to LyX is an enhancement to MultiMarkdown that allows the production of a  file. These files can be opened directly in LyX. As described on their web page:
\par}



{\pard \s7 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24\li720\ri720 LyX is a document processor that encourages an approach to writing based on the {\i structure} of your documents (WYSIWYM) and not simply their appearance (WYSIWYG). 
\par}

{\pard \s7 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24\li720\ri720 LyX combines the power and flexibility of TeX/LaTeX with the ease of use of a graphical interface. This results in world-class support for creation of mathematical content (via a fully integrated equation editor) and structured documents like academic articles, theses, and books. In addition, staples of scientific authoring such as reference list and index creation come standard. But you can also use LyX to create a letter or a novel or a theatre play or film script. A broad array of ready, well-designed document layouts are built in.{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chtfn {\pard \s7 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24\li720\ri720 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.lyx.org"}}{\fldrslt http://www.lyx.org}}
\par}
}
\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 MultiMarkdown already provides LaTeX support, so you may ask, why provide LyX output? There are two key areas where LyX stands out:
\par}

{\listtext \'95 }

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 Editing and \'93Tweaking\'94 the LaTeX product. While MultiMarkdown is powerful, it can’t support all of the capabilities of LaTeX. LyX provides a structured editing environment that will allow modifications to the final output without being a LaTeX expert. In addition it will make it easier to adapt to other document classes, beyond Memoir and Beamer. For example, I really like this \'93Tufte-Handout\'94 class.{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chtfn {\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 Inspired by Edward Tufte, author of four beautiful books on design: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/"}}{\fldrslt http://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/}}\line More information on the  class here: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://wiki.lyx.org/Layouts/Tufte-handout"}}{\fldrslt http://wiki.lyx.org/Layouts/Tufte-handout}}
\par}
}
\par}
{\listtext \'95 }
{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 Easy choice of output formats. The  and  functions of LyX provide a large number of output choices to include PDF, postscript, DVI, different HTML formats, and rich text. For example, the output to HTML using eLyXer is very attractive.
\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 Please note that the vast majority of my work has been using the LyX  output processor and have been successful. Given the packages utilized, with other output processors \'93your mileage may vary.\'94
\par}

{\pard \s1 \f1\fs32\ql\sb240\sa180\b {\*\bkmkstart howdoiusemultimarkdowntolyx}{\*\bkmkend howdoiusemultimarkdowntolyx}How do I use MultiMarkdown to LyX?\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 The LyX support is built into MultiMarkdown. You specify LyX output using the command line option  or  and specifying \'93lyx\'94:
\par}

{\pard \s7 \qj\sa180\f2\fs20\li360\ri360 multimarkdown -t lyx\

\par}


{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 In general, the metadata in the MultiMarkdown file will control the details of creating the  file.
\par}

{\pard \s2 \f1\fs28\ql\sb240\sa180\i\b {\*\bkmkstart latexpackages}{\*\bkmkend latexpackages}LaTeX Packages\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 Depending on the needs of the document class you are using and some of the metadata options, particular classes will be required.
\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 MultiMarkdown to LyX assumes the following packages and will add them to the  of the LyX document settings dialog:
\par}

\ls1\ilvl0 {\listtext \'95 }listings \'96 used in formatting codeblocks\
{\listtext \'95 }natbib\
{\listtext \'95 }nomencl\
{\listtext \'95 }booktabs\
{\listtext \'95 }beamer-fragile (only if you are using Beamer)\
{\listtext \'95 }varioref \'96 to improve page references in links\


{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 Be sure that these packages are installed in your LaTeX configuration before you attempt to produce output from LyX.
\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 In addition to the packages automatically included by MultiMarkdown, you can request that additional packages be added to this list via the  metadata entry (see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#packages"}}{\fldrslt {\i Packages}}}).
\par}

{\pard \s1 \f1\fs32\ql\sb240\sa180\b {\*\bkmkstart whatisdifferentaboutlyxdocuments}{\*\bkmkend whatisdifferentaboutlyxdocuments}What is different about LyX documents?\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 When you are creating a document that will be processed by LyX there are some differences from normal MultiMarkdown processing \'96 and even LaTeX targeted MultiMarkdown.
\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 Most of the differences are managed by utilizing the metadata at the beginning of the MultiMarkdown document. These options are described in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#metadata"}}{\fldrslt {\i MetaData}}}.
\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 Because of the way LyX utilizes BibTeX, and to remain consistent with BibTeX formatting, the formatting of citations is a bit constrained.
\par}

{\pard \s2 \f1\fs28\ql\sb240\sa180\i\b {\*\bkmkstart metadata}{\*\bkmkend metadata}MetaData\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 The LyX processor only looks at particular metadata entries. Other entries not described below are ignored, and you can leave them in place if you will be switching to other processors.
\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 It also re-uses some of the LaTeX metadata entries to the same purpose as the LaTeX processor with a similar effect, but perhaps without all of the options.
\par}

{\pard \s3 \f1\fs28\ql\sb240\sa180\b {\*\bkmkstart abstract}{\*\bkmkend abstract}Abstract\par}

{\pard \s0 \qj\sa180\f0\fs24 The  metadata encloses the value provided in the LyX  environment. It will be placed in the document as defined by the document class.
\par}

